    sensoryPathway: `Intestinal distension and cramping activate mechanoreceptors and nociceptors in the gut wall. Signals travel via splanchnic and vagal afferents to the spinal cord and brainstem. The urgency sensation results from rectal distension activating pelvic nerve afferents. Inflammatory mediators sensitize these pathways.`,

    localizationExplanation: `Small bowel diarrhea tends to be voluminous and watery without urgency or tenesmus. Large bowel/colonic diarrhea tends to be smaller volume but more frequent, with urgency, tenesmus, and possibly blood/mucus. Location of cramping may suggest involved segment.`,
