    sensoryPathway: `Photoreceptors in the retina convert light to electrical signals. These
signals are processed by bipolar and ganglion cells, forming the optic nerve. At the optic
chiasm, nasal fibers cross, so each brain hemisphere receives information from the opposite
visual field. The lateral geniculate nucleus relays signals to the primary visual cortex.
Damage at different levels produces predictable visual field defects - understanding this
anatomy helps localize lesions.`,

    localizationExplanation: `The pattern of vision loss indicates where the problem is.
Monocular vision loss = eye or optic nerve (before chiasm). Bitemporal hemianopia = chiasm
(pituitary tumor). Homonymous hemianopia = post-chiasmal (stroke). Central scotoma =
macula or optic nerve. Tunnel vision = glaucoma (peripheral field loss). Floaters/flashes
= vitreous or retina. Diplopia = cranial nerves (3, 4, 6) or brain stem.`,
